<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">Urban rivers are Chennai's most contested surface-process arena.</p>
  <p>The Cooum and the Adyar aren't just rivers. They're decades of policy fights — restoration plans, encroachment removal, sewage interception, flood mitigation — and competing claims about what each river <em>is</em>. Today: river-process vocabulary (drainage basin, channel, floodplain, delta, estuary), the two case studies (Cooum + Adyar), and the OPVL move that will be central to your <a href="/units/unit-2/assessment-landscape-reading/">Landscape Reading</a>.</p>
  <p>The closing discussion question — <strong>should urban rivers be channelized, or restored?</strong> — has no clean answer. Engineering says channelize (predictable flow, less flooding, more land). Ecology says restore (riparian habitat, flood buffer, water quality). Politics says something in between. Today the question lands; in Block 9 you'll defend a recommendation on something equally contested.</p>
</section>

