<section class="block-section do">
  <span class="section-tag">Do</span>
  <h2>Today's work — choose one path</h2>
  <p class="sub">All four paths end with at least one structured OPVL on a river source. The path you pick is about which river, how many sources, and which move you stretch on.</p>
  <div class="choice-intro">
    <strong>Learning Intention:</strong> I can apply OPVL to three contested sources about an urban river AND identify which source's Limitation most affects how I'd cite it in a Landscape Reading.
  </div>
  <div class="choice-board">
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">A</div>
      <div class="choice-title">OPVL all three Cooum sources + synthesis (default)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Full OPVL on each of the three Cooum sources from the Interact activity. Write a 3-sentence synthesis identifying the single most-contested claim across the three sources, with which source you'd cite for what.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Default</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">B</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Stress-test AI against government source</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Take the AI-generated source and the government source. Find a specific factual disagreement between them. Document it. Which source is more credible on this specific claim, and why? Use the <a href="/ai-partners/the-source-evaluator/">Source Evaluator</a> to walk the OPVL if helpful.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Stretch</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">C</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Apply to the Adyar instead</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Find your own three sources (one government, one news, one AI) about the Adyar River or its estuary. Apply OPVL to each. Same synthesis move as Path A but for a different river.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Choice</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">D</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Channelize-or-restore micro-debate prep</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">For students who want to lead the closing 5-minute discussion. Pick a side (channelize or restore). Build the strongest case using evidence from the three sources. Acknowledge the strongest counter-argument. Prepare a 90-second opener.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Pairs · Practice</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="block-section show">
  <span class="section-tag">Show</span>
  <h2>What you're submitting today</h2>
  <p class="sub">OPVL is the T/T thread for the Landscape Reading. Today's submission is your first concrete practice on a real Chennai source set.</p>
  <div class="submission-callout">
    <div class="label">OPVL on three river sources + a 3-sentence synthesis</div>
    <p>Three OPVLs (one per source), plus a 3-sentence synthesis. The synthesis names <strong>the single most contested claim</strong> across the three sources — and which source you'd cite for what, with reasoning. Specificity in the Limitations is what separates T/T 7-8 from T/T 3-4.</p>
    <a href="#" class="rubric-link">Submit via Google Classroom →</a>
  </div>
  <p class="rubric-meta">
    <strong>Rubric link:</strong> "OPVL applied to 3 sources including the AI source; at least one Limitation is specific and substantive" is the T/T 7-8 description on the <a href="/units/unit-2/assessment-landscape-reading/">Landscape Reading rubric</a>. Today's practice is the rehearsal for it; the 3-source OPVL locks as Component 3 at Block 7. See the <a href="/foundations/the-rubric/">rubric</a>.
  </p>
</section>

